{{coord|40.707177|N|74.012224|W|display=title}} {{Infobox building | name = 65 Broadway | image = 65 Broadway 001.JPG | image_caption = | former_names = Railway Express Company Building, American Express Building, J.J. Kenny Company Building | alternate_names = Standard & Poors Building | building_type = Office | architectural_style = [[Neoclassical architecture|Neoclassical]] | address = 63-65 Broadway | location_city = [[Financial District, Manhattan|Financial District]], [[Manhattan]], [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]] | location_country = [[United States]] | coordinates = {{coord|40.707177|N|74.012224|W|format=dms}} | start_date = 1916 | completion_date = 1917 | renovation_date = 1999 | height = {{convert|232.59|ft|m}} | floor_count = 21 | architect = [[James Renwick Jr.|Renwick, Aspinwall & Tucker]] | embedded = {{Designation list | embed = yes | designation1 = NYC | designation1_date = 12 December 1995 | designation1_number = [http://s-media.nyc.gov/agencies/lpc/lp/1932.pdf LP-1932] }} | references = <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.emporis.com/buildings/115684/standard-poors-building-new-york-city-ny-usa|title=Stanard & Poors Building|website=[[Emporis]]|accessdate=29 March 2017}}</ref> }}
The '''American Express Building''', also known as '''65 Broadway,''' is a building between Morris and Rector Streets in the [[Financial District, Manhattan|Financial District]] of [[Manhattan]], [[New York City]]. It was built in 1914-1917 and was designed by [[James L. Aspinwall]] of the firm of [[Renwick, Aspinwall and Russell|Renwick, Aspinwall & Tucker]] in the [[Neoclassical architecture|Neoclassical style]]. The 21-story building goes through to [[Trinity Place]], and was the headquarters of [[American Express]] until 1975.<ref name=nycland>{{cite nycland}}, p.11</ref> The building is now sometimes called the '''Standard & Poors Building''', but should not be confused with another building using that name at [[Cunard Building (New York City)|25 Broadway]]. This Class A office building has 10 elevators, is [[Leadership in Energy and Environmental Design|LEED]]-certified, and qualifies for the Lower Manhattan Energy Program.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://42floors.com/ny/new-york/65-broadway|publisher=Newmark Grubb Knight Frank, Joshua Gosin|title=65 Broadway|date=January 2014|accessdate=2014-01-23}}{{Dead link|date=November 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>
[[File:American Express Company Building 65 Broadway entrance.jpg|thumb|left|The entrance to the American Express Company Building at 65 Broadway in 2012.]]The [[New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission]] designated the concrete and steel-frame building a [[List of New York City Landmarks|New York City landmark]] in December 1995.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nyc.gov/html/lpc/downloads/pdf/reports/amerexpress.pdf|title=Designation List 269, LP-1932|publisher=[[New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission]]|date=December 12, 1995|accessdate=2008-04-16}}</ref>
